This law sets limitations on policy-based lending by the International Bank for Reconstruction and Development (IBRD) and requires the US Secretary of Treasury to take necessary steps to encourage the IBRD to limit such lending. The aggregate value of policy-based loans by the IBRD in any fiscal year must not exceed 25% of all loans made in such fiscal year, and loans to a particular government must not exceed 50% of all loans made to that government during any three consecutive fiscal years. The US Executive Director of the IBRD must actively seek the adoption of these limits by the board of Executive Directors, and until then, the Secretary of Treasury must engage in discussions with other member countries to secure their consent and cooperation. This law was enacted in 1988 and applies to fiscal years 1990 through 1995.}
