This section of U.S. Code makes provisions for the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to develop a methodology for measuring military spending by developing nations. The U.S. Executive Director of the Fund is required to use their voice and vote to urge the IMF to continue this work and provide progress reports to Congress. The Fund is also required to provide annual reports on the estimate of military spending by each developing country and include analysis of military spending in every article IV consultation with a developing country. This provision was added to the U.S. Code in 1992. It reflects a concern among some policymakers about the negative economic impact of high military spending in developing nations. The provision seeks to encourage transparency and accountability in military spending and promote economic development in these countries. It is unclear how effective this provision has been in achieving these goals.}
